---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';

import '../../styles/global.css';

// Importing SEO data for the About page
import { aboutPageSeo } from '../../data/js/seo/siteSeo.js';

import seoData from '@/data/js/services/adepde.js';
---

<Layout
  seo={{
    title: `${seoData.meta.title} - Indivirtus`,
    description: seoData.meta.description,
    keywords: seoData.meta.keywords,
    canonical: seoData.meta.canonicalUrl,
    image: seoData.image.path.src,
    url: seoData.pageLink,
    schema: seoData.schema,
  }}
>
  <article class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 py-12">
    <header class="mb-12">
      <h1 class="mb-4 text-4xl font-bold text-blue-900">
        Understanding ADE, PDE, OEL, and OEB Assessments for API Safety and Compliance
      </h1>
      <div class="mb-6 w-24 border-b-2 border-blue-200"></div>
    </header>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-800">Introduction</h2>
      <div class="prose max-w-none">
        <p>
          In pharmaceutical manufacturing, ensuring the safety of workers and patients is paramount. To establish safe
          exposure limits for Active Pharmaceutical Ingredients (APIs) in workplace settings, expert toxicology
          assessments are required.
        </p>
        <p>
          These assessments—<strong>Acceptable Daily Exposure (ADE)</strong>, <strong
            >Permitted Daily Exposure (PDE)</strong
          >, <strong>Occupational Exposure Limit (OEL)</strong>, and <strong>Occupational Exposure Band (OEB)</strong
          >—are critical for regulatory compliance, cleaning validation, facility design, and Good Manufacturing
          Practice (GMP) adherence.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12 rounded-lg bg-blue-50 p-6">
      <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-800">Why Are ADE, PDE, OEL, and OEB Assessments Necessary?</h2>
      <div class="prose max-w-none">
        <p>
          Pharmaceutical facilities must ensure that workers are not exposed to harmful levels of APIs, while also
          guaranteeing that cross-contamination does not compromise drug safety.
        </p>

        <h3 class="mt-6 text-xl font-medium text-blue-700">Key reasons for these assessments include:</h3>
        <ul class="list-disc space-y-2 pl-6">
          <li><strong>Worker Safety:</strong> Protecting employees from hazardous API exposure.</li>
          <li><strong>Cleaning Validation:</strong> Ensuring equipment is free from harmful residues.</li>
          <li><strong>Facility Design:</strong> Designing containment strategies to minimize exposure.</li>
          <li><strong>Regulatory Compliance:</strong> Meeting EMA, ICH Q3D, and ISPE standards.</li>
        </ul>

        <p class="mt-4">
          Certified toxicologists (such as <strong>ERT/DABT-certified professionals</strong>) conduct these evaluations
          using toxicological data and scientific literature to derive scientifically justified limits.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="mb-6 text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-800">Breaking Down ADE, PDE, OEL, and OEB</h2>

      <div class="grid gap-8 md:grid-cols-2">
        <div class="rounded-lg border-t-4 border-blue-500 bg-white p-6 shadow-md">
          <h3 class="mb-3 text-xl font-semibold text-blue-700">1. Acceptable Daily Exposure (ADE)</h3>
          <p>
            The <strong>ADE</strong> represents the maximum amount of an API that a person can be exposed to daily over a
            lifetime without adverse effects.
          </p>

          <h4 class="mt-4 mb-2 font-medium text-blue-600">Key Aspects:</h4>
          <ul class="list-disc space-y-1 pl-5">
            <li>Used in <strong>cleaning validation</strong> to determine safe residue limits.</li>
            <li>Based on <strong>NOAEL (No Observed Adverse Effect Level)</strong> and safety factors.</li>
            <li>Complies with <strong>ICH Q3D</strong> guidelines for elemental impurities.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="rounded-lg border-t-4 border-green-500 bg-white p-6 shadow-md">
          <h3 class="mb-3 text-xl font-semibold text-green-700">2. Permitted Daily Exposure (PDE)</h3>
          <p>The <strong>PDE</strong> is similar to ADE but is often used interchangeably in regulatory contexts.</p>

          <h4 class="mt-4 mb-2 font-medium text-green-600">Key Aspects:</h4>
          <ul class="list-disc space-y-1 pl-5">
            <li>Applied in <strong>risk assessment for cross-contamination</strong>.</li>
            <li>Follows <strong>EMA and ISPE</strong> standards.</li>
            <li>Considers <strong>chronic toxicity, reproductive effects, and carcinogenicity</strong>.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="rounded-lg border-t-4 border-purple-500 bg-white p-6 shadow-md">
          <h3 class="mb-3 text-xl font-semibold text-purple-700">3. Occupational Exposure Limit (OEL)</h3>
          <p>
            The <strong>OEL</strong> indicates the airborne concentration of an API that workers can be exposed to over an
            8-hour workday.
          </p>

          <h4 class="mt-4 mb-2 font-medium text-purple-600">Key Aspects:</h4>
          <ul class="list-disc space-y-1 pl-5">
            <li>Critical for <strong>worker safety programs</strong>.</li>
            <li>Expressed in <strong>μg/m³ or mg/m³</strong>.</li>
            <li>Used to design <strong>engineering controls (ventilation, containment)</strong>.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="rounded-lg border-t-4 border-orange-500 bg-white p-6 shadow-md">
          <h3 class="mb-3 text-xl font-semibold text-orange-700">4. Occupational Exposure Band (OEB)</h3>
          <p>The <strong>OEB</strong> categorizes APIs based on their toxicity and potency.</p>

          <h4 class="mt-4 mb-2 font-medium text-orange-600">Key Aspects:</h4>
          <ul class="list-disc space-y-1 pl-5">
            <li>Ranges from <strong>OEB 1 (low risk) to OEB 5 (highest risk)</strong>.</li>
            <li>Guides <strong>containment strategies and PPE requirements</strong>.</li>
            <li>Aligns with <strong>ISPE's Risk-MaPP</strong> guidelines.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12 rounded-lg bg-gray-100 p-6">
      <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-800">How Are These Assessments Conducted?</h2>
      <div class="prose max-w-none">
        <p>Expert toxicologists follow a structured approach:</p>

        <div class="mt-6 space-y-6">
          <div>
            <h3 class="mb-2 text-xl font-medium text-gray-700">Step 1: Data Collection</h3>
            <ul class="list-disc space-y-1 pl-6">
              <li>Review <strong>toxicological studies (animal/human data)</strong>.</li>
              <li>Identify <strong>NOAEL, LOAEL, and benchmark doses</strong>.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h3 class="mb-2 text-xl font-medium text-gray-700">Step 2: Apply Safety Factors</h3>
            <ul class="list-disc space-y-1 pl-6">
              <li>Adjust for <strong>interspecies differences and intraspecies variability</strong>.</li>
              <li>Use <strong>ICH Q3D</strong> guidelines for elemental impurities.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h3 class="mb-2 text-xl font-medium text-gray-700">Step 3: Derive Exposure Limits</h3>
            <ul class="list-disc space-y-1 pl-6">
              <li>Calculate <strong>ADE/PDE</strong> using dose-response data.</li>
              <li>Establish <strong>OELs</strong> based on inhalation toxicity.</li>
              <li>Assign <strong>OEBs</strong> based on potency and toxicity.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h3 class="mb-2 text-xl font-medium text-gray-700">Step 4: Certification & Compliance</h3>
            <ul class="list-disc space-y-1 pl-6">
              <li>Reports are certified by <strong>ERT/DABT</strong> professionals.</li>
              <li>Ensure alignment with <strong>EMA, ICH, and ISPE</strong> standards.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-800">Applications in Pharmaceutical Operations</h2>

      <div class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2">
        <div class="rounded-lg border-l-4 border-blue-500 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="mb-3 text-xl font-semibold text-blue-700">1. Cleaning Validation</h3>
          <ul class="list-disc space-y-1 pl-5">
            <li>ADE/PDE values set <strong>maximum allowable carryover (MACO)</strong> limits.</li>
            <li>Ensures equipment cleaning procedures eliminate harmful residues.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="rounded-lg border-l-4 border-green-500 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="mb-3 text-xl font-semibold text-green-700">2. Facility Design & Containment</h3>
          <ul class="list-disc space-y-1 pl-5">
            <li>OEL/OEB ratings determine <strong>containment requirements</strong>.</li>
            <li>Prevents cross-contamination in <strong>multi-product facilities</strong>.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="rounded-lg border-l-4 border-purple-500 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="mb-3 text-xl font-semibold text-purple-700">3. Worker Safety Programs</h3>
          <ul class="list-disc space-y-1 pl-5">
            <li>OELs guide <strong>exposure monitoring and PPE selection</strong>.</li>
            <li>OEBs help classify <strong>handling procedures</strong>.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="rounded-lg border-l-4 border-orange-500 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="mb-3 text-xl font-semibold text-orange-700">4. Regulatory Submissions</h3>
          <ul class="list-disc space-y-1 pl-5">
            <li>Required for <strong>GMP compliance and inspections</strong>.</li>
            <li>Supports <strong>risk assessments for FDA, EMA</strong>.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="bg-primary-light mb-12 rounded-lg p-8 text-white">
      <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-semibold">Why Choose Certified Toxicology Reports?</h2>
      <div class="prose text-gray max-w-none">
        <p>
          Given the critical nature of these assessments, they must be conducted by qualified professionals. <strong
            >ERT/DABT-certified toxicologists</strong
          > ensure:
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-4 list-disc space-y-2 pl-6">
          <li><strong>Scientifically robust limits</strong> backed by data</li>
          <li><strong>Regulatory compliance</strong> with EMA, ICH, and ISPE</li>
          <li><strong>Defensible risk assessments</strong> for audits and inspections</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-800">Conclusion</h2>
      <div class="prose max-w-none">
        <p>
          ADE, PDE, OEL, and OEB assessments are essential for pharmaceutical safety and compliance. These toxicological
          evaluations protect workers, prevent cross-contamination, and ensure adherence to <strong
            >GMP, ICH Q3D, EMA, and ISPE</strong
          > guidelines.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4">
          By relying on <strong>certified toxicology reports</strong>, pharmaceutical companies can confidently
          establish safe exposure limits, optimize facility design, and maintain regulatory compliance.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <div class="rounded-lg border border-blue-200 bg-blue-50 p-6 text-center">
      <h3 class="mb-3 text-xl font-semibold text-blue-800">Need Expert Toxicology Assessments?</h3>
      <p class="mb-4">
        Ensure your facility meets safety and compliance standards with <strong
          >ERT/DABT-certified ADE, PDE, OEL, and OEB reports</strong
        >.
      </p>
      <a href="/contact-us" class="button">Contact Us Today</a>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>
